{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_ironsprings_ver01/data/sn84020064/00414217709/1927010101/0001.xml":{"full_text":"Douglas Is the Secifid Largest City on the Southern United States Border and the Gateway to Sonora, the Treasure House of Me.%%0\nSaturday and Sunday gen\nerally fair; little change in\ntemperature.\nVOL. XXIV.\nDOUGUASITES SEE PROSPEROUS YEAR FOR CITY\n3-SUIE MEET\nJUUOURIS.TEI\n111 DEAOLQCI\nArizona, California and I\nNevada Agree on Wat<r\nDivision, However.\nTO MEET\" AGAIN\nJpwer Levy in State jn\nWhich Electricity Is Gen\nerated Causes Trouble.;\nLOS ANGELES, Dec. \u00a71 j\n(AP) The tri-state conf4\"-i\nence on problems growiig\nout of proposed develop- j\n'Tient of the Colorado riwj\nadjourned indefinitely here\ntoday after three weeks,\nof deliberations that re- j\njilted in an agreement be- j\nNevada, Arizona and\nCalifornia on division of\nwaters to the lower basin\nstates but left the delegates;\ndeadlocked on the question\nof what power revenues\nArizona should receive for\nenergy generated within\nthat state. Jj j\nCharles P. Squires of Nevada, i\nman of the conferenee, issued the fol- j\nlow in s' statement: \u201cThe commission:\nerk of Arizona, California and Nevada\nat the session today discussed the j\nmatter of revenues to be derived by i\nthe states in which power may lie\ndeveloped on the baKs of taxation. 1\nIt was conceded by California com-\nmissioners that the states in which\npower is to be developed hav< tin-j\nright to a reasonable revenue from\npower developed, but the confi rmee\ndisagreed on the question of placing\na limitation on the amount which\ncould be levied.\n\u201cCommissi! oner Mad dock (Thomas\nMnddock of Arizona) presented a. pro-,\nposal which embodied the idea That a j\nhoard of arbitration composed of one 1\nmember from each of the three states\nand one representative of the federal\ngovernment sh;ould be constituted to\nwhich questions as to the reasonable\namount of any levy made by either of I\nthe states might he submitted for de- j\ncj.r\u2019on.\n\u201cThe conference adjourned this aft\nernoon t meet again some day next\nweek, probably Thursday. The gen\neral trend of negotiation's is toward i,\n(Continued on Page Twelve.)\nNew Year Brings Promise Os Job\nFor Nearly Every American, Says\nHoover; Great Business Outlook\nWASHINGTON', Dec. 31 UP).\u2014' The\nNew Year brings a promise of a jot\n.for nearly every American, Secretar;\nHoover said today, and a business\noutlook that is at least free fron\nfear of a violent commercial or finan\ncial cataclysm. Despite agricultural\nconditions and some recent recession*\nfi n production and consumption, the\nnation, in his opinion, can look for\nward hopefully to a continuation of\nits economic progress.\nA reply to requests for opinion on\nNew Year's economic prospects cat\nonly be based upon the economic cur\nrents already born of the old year,\u2019\nthe co-mmerce secretary said in a\nformal statement.\n\u201cNew and unknown currents will\ninter in ihe New Year, so there is\nno such thing as assured economic\nprophecy.\n\u201cNo one will deny that 1926 has\nshown the highest; total production\n\"DOUGLAS DAILY DISDAfGH\nCOL H, DU PONI\nDIES WHILE\nlIBED ON FRIDAY\n11\nSop and Daughter at Bed\nside\u2014Civil War Veteran,\nStatesman and Financier.\ni WILMINGTON, Del., Dec. 31 (A*).\u2014\ni Stricken by a heart attack while lit\nj bed, Colonel Henry DuPont died at\nj home near here this morning. Onl>\nj Ids son, Henry F. DuPont, and his\n1 daughter, Mrs. Francis' E. Crowin\nshield, were able to reach his bedside\nbefore the end came.\nColonel DuPiont was 88 years old\nj He distinguished hums elf in the Civil\nI war, was a former United States sen.\nator from Delaware and a cousin o!\nj the present Senator Coleman T. Du-,\nj Pont. He was seriously ill several\nI months ago, but apparently had re\ncovered, except for a. cold which wa*\ni confronting' him to ins bed when his\nheart failed.\nj For several years, Colonel DuPont\nhad spent the greater part of his\ntime i n his home, and with his farm\ning interests at Winterthur, neai\nhere. He occasionally went to Wash-,\ning-ton and was planning to spend\nj the remainder of the winter there\nj when iie dieel.\nFuneral services will be conducted\nSunday afternoon at Christ Episcopal\nchurch by Bishop Cook and the Rev,\nFrederick D. Ashton. Interment will\nLe in the DuPont family cemetery.\nI Former United States Senator Henry\n'A. DuPont of Delaware, who repre\nsented that state in the senate from\n1905 to 1917, was born in Newcastle\ncounty, Delaware, on July 30, 1838,\nHe was a g-andston of Fleuthert\nTrenee du Pont de Nemours, a gun:\npowder manufacturer, and a g-reai\nj grandson of Pierre Samuel du Pont\n[de Nemours, a famous Flench econo,\nmist and statesman who died in thi\nUnited States in 1817.\nGraduated from the United States\nMilitary academy at West Point on\nMay 6, 1861 at the head of his class\nyoung DuPont was oomrnissioned a\nlieutenant in the Union army arid\nserved with distinction throughout\nthe Civil war. lining breveted a Ueu\nj tenant colonel for valorous services at\nj the battle of Cedar Creek, Va. Sub\nsequently he wa\u00bb awarded a congres\nsional medal of honor \u201cfor, gallantry\nand voluntary exposure to the enemy\u2019s\nfire at a cU'tical moment during this\nbattle.\" Other engagements in which\nI lie fought were at Newmarket, Pied-.\nI mont, Lexington, Lynchburg, Berry\n-I\\| lie, Winchester, Mason\u2019s creek and\nHalltown. He was at one time In\ncommand of an artillery brigade in\nGeneral Cook's corps. Previously he\nhad served as acting assistant adjut-\nI ant general in charge of the troops\nIJn New York harbor. He resigned\nfrom the army in 1875 after having\nbeen in command of Fortress Monroe\nand several other important irj litary\nposts.\ni, He became president and genera;\n(Continued on Page Twelve)\nnd consumption of industrial com\nlodities of any year iti the history\ni f the United States. Except in the.\nixtile industry and coal industry it\nlas been a year of high degree of\nmployment which has been accorn\nili'.shed by the highest peak In real\n/ages, because wage income as a\nvhole has slightly inerea\u2019sed and cost\nf living slightly decreased during\nthe year.\n\u201cManufacturing the service Indus\nries, and commerce generally have\ncontinued to improve their methods,\nto reduce costs, arid to improve serv\nices. in aggregate, each industry ap\npears to show substantial profits e--\nce-pt the textile and some part of the\ncoal industry.\n\u201cWhile there has been a slacken\ning in production and demand for\nseveral staple lines during the past\nfew weeks, we enter the New Year\n(Continued on Page Twelve)\nDOUGLAS, ARIZONA. SATURDAY MORNING, JANUARY, 1, 1927.\nAh\u2014We've Picked Up Another New Station\nHsaa eveRVBocW-\nA!OW /-9/r\nveoM sTaToa f i,\nI- 9-2-7 /X\\\nv'E will 5/arToff B ylcoJTug m A\nwhisTlen, blow/mgMo/?aisami? IfPtlPw /#XX, X\n/Mu SELLS AFIeK WHICM IS I luff/ /V A A\nVOU WILL BE BY /PjHpfj\n;-\\V i iTfUi assisTakT- i^**^**h\nVTILL Be AO MRjfcT&ER. C\nAnnouncements* XX XX\n!ASSOCIATED PRESS RECEIVES NEW;\nYEAR GREETING ALMOST 17 HOURS!\nBEFORE THE NEW YEAR HITS U. S.j\nW YEAR MET\nWITH JOYOUS j\nj\nI\nAs twilight deepened into darknessj\non the eve of the New Year, the city!\nof Douglas was crowded with visitors j\nfrom all parts of the county who ar-;\nrived in cars and by train to spend the j\nnight in this city attending some one!\nof the numerous New Year parties. I\nI The hotels reported to the Dispatch at\nj dusk that they had filled more rooms j\nI in a shorter length of time than for,\nj many months.\ni At the Gadsden alone, between 4j\no'clock and 4:30 in the afternoon y%s-i\nterday, 14 persons registered and took!\ni rooms, but it was noted that none of j\nj the new arrivals showed any signs of\nwanting to retire early. There were\nj sounds of revelry by night and strains\nj of dance music floated on the balmy\nf air as the evening advanced and at\nj midnight pandemonium br.ike loose,\nj Whistles shrieked and roared. Guns\nland pistols cracked, sirens moaned,\nj horns tooted, boys and men cheeredl\nland shouted, nor did the noise entirelvj\ndie away for hours. Now and then,\nuntil dawn approached some late rev-1\ne'er would be heard to fire off alt au-j\ntomatic pistol or a shotgun would roar|\nin the suburbs, where someone had|\nfound an extra shell overlooked in thej\nexcitement of the earlier exuberance.]\nExeryone seemed perfectly, delight-!\nI edly happy and there was an atmo-j\nabroad that was different from\ntlie New Year of the past,\nfew years. The happiness seemed to!\nbe more real and more deeply rooted.j\nPerhaps live genuine prosperity that j\ntiie dead year 1926 brought to Douglas)\nand to this county may have created!\nthis glorious happiness and the old year]\nwas escorted into oblivion with joy\nand thankfulness, while with gaiety]\nand confidence the citizens turned to]\nthe future and welcomed the New j\nYear, 1927,\nCOMPLETE LEASED WIRE REPORT OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nj NEW YORK, Dec. 31 (TP). \u2014A greet-\ning from the year 1937, flung by\nradii* 10,000 'miles across the world!\njinto the teeth of time, ,was received j\niby the Associated Press in New York I\nwhere 1926 had almost 17 hours still\nto run.\nI The feat was hailed an an unpar.\njaileled achievement both in news j\ngathering and 'marine radio comma j\nnication by David Sarnoff, genera;\nmanager of the \u2019tadio Corporation oi:\nj America, whose co-operation made I\npossible the exchange of greetings\nbetween the two years and the two\n\u25a0tides of the earth.\nEarly today, the Associated Press\nI sent a greeting to a score of world\ntourists on the Cunard line Carinthia\njin Cook Strait, New Zealand. Be., j\nj cause of the difference in time, the 1\nmessage, although delivered almost\ni nstanteously, was received on tlw\nj Carinthia as the passengers were;\nj celebrating New Year's eve.\nAs the old year died across the\nj world and the new was horn, the\npassengers sent a return greeting to\nNew York, received here at 7:24 a. j\nm., December 31, almost 17 hours\n\u201cbefore it was sent.\"\nThe feat, Sarnoff told the Assoc-i,\nated Press, \u201cis more than an accotn-\nplishment in direct communication by\nradio over a distance of half the\nworld\u2019s surface. It I s in reality the\n'circumnavigation of the globe by radio j\nthrough the medium of short wav.-\nj communication, for radio waves travel\njin all directions.\nI \u201cThe experiment gives further poinij\nIto the call made by the United States\nJ government for a 'world meeting in j\n1 Washington in 1927 to revise the in\nj fernational radio telegraph convert- I\nt\u2019'on of 1912. This provides that a j\n'ship a sea in communicating' with land;\nmust do so through the nearer\ncoasta l station. The present experi- i\nj ment has proved the possibility oi j\njiiirect radio communication with a\nI ship at sea over unlimited distances.'\ni C\nKIM.EII itY At TO\nj PHOENIX, Dec. 31 (TP)\u2014Juan Pc-j\nj ralta, 38, was killed almost instantly]\nj today when a motor car driven b.v|\nj Isaac Romley overturned after oollid-j\ning with one driven by Pat Syler.\nPROSECUTOR TO\nTRY EVAMST\nEOS ANGELES, Dec. 31 (TP). \u2014A\ndefenite policy that Aiimee Semple\nMcPherson and her three co-del'end\nants must stand trial in superior\ncourt on charges growing out of hei\ndisappearance and story of k,ipnap-\u2018\ning has been adopted by the district\nattorney\u2019s office the prosecuting at\ntorneys declared tonight. Informa\ntion against the au tram-nai red evain\ngelist, her former radio man, Ken\nneth G. Orm i stion, her mother, Mrs.\nMinnie Kennedy, and Mrs.' Lorraine\nWiseman Sielaff wai be filed im-.\nmediately following the report oi\nthe county (grand jury which will\nresume its investigation of the cas-i\nTuesday.\nMrs. Ruth Peters Ormfston, e.-'\n'.ranged wife of the radio operator,\nmay be an important witness for the\nprosecution, it was said. She will\narrive in. Los Angeles from her ho-mt\nin Sidney, Australia, the middle ot\nnext month. She was recently\nquoted as saying that she had re\net-'ved an \u201c(important\u201d leter from\nMrs. McPherson, dated May 18, tihe\nday the evangelist vanished and the\nday prior to the appearance of Orm\nfston at Carmel w.m a mystery wo.\nman. who the state contends was\nMrs. McPherson.\nAd-A-Man Club Reaches\nSummit Os Pike\u2019s Peak\nAs Part Os Annual Hike\nCOLORADO SPRINGS. Colo., Dec.\n:tI (TP) \u2014A brilliant, display of vari\nes-lored flares and rockets at S>\no\u2019clock tonight indicated to Colo\nrado Springs and the state that\nthe members of the famous Aii-\nY-llaii club had reached the sum\nmit of Pikes Peak, through utiles\nof drifting snows, anil were pre\npared to gleet the New Year at\ni midnight with giant beacons of\nlight front the Top of the World,\niFIYE CHINESE\nTO BE HANGED\ni DURING MARCH\ni 71\nj\nSlayers of Kingman Res\ni taurant Owner Sentenced\nby Mohave Judge.\ni\nKINGMAN, Dec. \u2019G.\u2014OP)\u2014Five Chi-\niiese from California today were sen\ntenced to die on tne gallows in the\nstate penitentiary at Florence, March!\nj 11, for the slaying of Tom King, King- j\ni man restaurant keeper, on the night of j\nOctober 20. The quintet was convicted'\nI of first degree murder by three Mo- j\nj have county juries which set a record\nfor \u201cMohave county justice.\u201d\nj It took only five days to try and j\nconvict the five Chinese youths\u2014By j\nSam, Wong Long, Shiu Chin, Jiu Har\nland Gen Ken Lung\u2014all members of;\nI the Bing Kong tong. King was aj\n'member of the Hr.ji Slogs. The third\njury which heard the consolidated cases'J\nof Lung, Har and Long returned aver- i\ni diet after only 25 minutes deliberation, j\nJudge 1-1. F. Bollinger of the superio'r\ncourt, who heard the eases, denied the\nmotion of L. L. Wallace, defense at\ntorney, for a. new trial and the latter\ngave notice of an appeal to the state,\nj supreme court. He offered little or no\n\u2018defense during the trials and his ap\nj peal, he indicated,' would be based on\n!an allegation of unfair trials and on\nthe fact that the principal prosecution\ntestimony Was the transcript of the\ntestimony of Don On. American-born\nChinese boy, at the preliminary hear- j\ning of tfhe five.\nDon On disappeared on the eve of\nt the trial of By Sam, the first of the\ni five to go to trial, after telegraphing\nj his grandfather in San Francisco that\nihe feared for his life. On was one of\ntwo eye witnesses to the murder of\nj Kipg.\nj Three of the convicted Chinese are\nfrom Los Angeles and the others are\nfrom San Bernard ino and Needles,'\ni Calif.\nWallace indicated also that he felt\n(Continued on Page Twelve.)*\nLawrence Moss Guilty\nMurder; Imprisonment\nFor Life Recommended\nPHOENIX, Dec. 31 Lawrence\nMoms, IS), Imy bandit, was convicted\nof first degree murder by n jur>\nin the Maricopa county superior\ncourt this afternoon in connection\nwith the fatal shooting Novemitei\n1M of W. <i. Perry, a storekeeper.\nThe jury was \u00bb>ut about twe\nhours.\nPerry was shot to death when\nhe refused to comply with an order)\nof Moss\u2019 to throw up his hands.\nTlie hoy\u2019s defense was ipsanity,\nHe has just been released from\nthe State Industrial school at Fort\n(\u25a0rant, where he was serving a\nthird term.\nThe jury recommended life I in-,\nprisonment.\nANTI-SALOON LEAGUE CHIEF SAYS\nPOISONS SHOULD BE KEPT IN ALL\nINDUSTRIAL ALCOHOL AT PRESENT\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 31 iTP).\u2014A din- views, Wheeler agreed that poisonous\nmission between Secretary Mellon and adulterants should be eliminated as\nWayne B> Wheeler, of the Anti-Saloon soon as possible.\nleague, on poison liquor today brought I Mellon declared that wood alcoho*\nforth a roderation from the treasury still was a component of the de\nchief that, the government does no* j naturing formula but government\nintend to endanger the lives of drink- j chemists were hoping shortly to pro\ntrs in its adulteration of industrial buce a harmless l.ut nauseating adult\nalcohol. jerant. The Anti-Saloon league leader\nWheeler went to Mellon's office to] also was assured by the treasury se<*-\nprotest against the government's plan i rotary that preventive steps were\nto abandon the denaturing of Indus- 1 eing maintained to stop any flow of\ntrial alcohol with persons to prevent {unadulterated industrial alcohol into\ntin- passage into bootleg channels. j bootleg channels, while the chemists\nHe held that wood alcohol should j were formulati ng' new denaturants.\nlie cmitfmieil as an adulterant until! Government chemists expressed hope\nother effective substitutes were dis- today that the new ingredient aldehot;\ncovered to make 'industrial a 1:ohoI which will he used in denaturing\nunfit for beverage pur-poses. formulae hereafter, will prove a sub\nSecretary Mellon, however, declared istitute eventually for wood alcohol\nhe was not in favor of any denatur- j This chemical is composed of a form\nf which would fatally poison Amer- j< f crank case oil and is expected to\ncitizens even to enforce thejgive to the alcohol a very distasteful\nj substance which it will he very hard\nAfter the secretary had outlined his Ito el iminate by distillation.\nN. Y., Dec. 31. UP)- er\neasy; electrolytic spot and\nfutures 13.25 to 13.37. Lead\ndull, spot 7.80. Bar stl\nver 54.\nmm m\nMl I e\nH FACES IIS\nf\nMayor Hinton Expects Rap\nj id Growth of City During\n1927, He States.\n!tardy boosts\nHubbell, Dowell, Graves,\nSouers, Buckley, Faulk\nner and Glenn Optimistic.\nI\n\nWelcome 1927, with the\nprosperity that you bring\nto Douglas! The concensus\nof opinion among city of\nficials, business men and\ncitizens of Douglas is that\nthe new year ushered in\nlast night means the dawn\nof a new era of prosperity\nfor Douglas.\nOutstanding among the things htat\nherald prosperity for Douglas and this\nsection are the construction of the\nnew lead smelter Here by the Phelps\nDodge corporation, the opening of the\nnow copper smelters here, soon to be\nblown in, the revival of mining\nthroughout the state, the general\nprospects for heavy crops during the\ncoming year find ;he general business\nprosperity of the city.\nA. R. HINTON\nMayor of the City of Doug'lns\n\"I feel that the New fear means\ntlie dawn of an era of unusual pros\nperity for Douglas, with everything\nindicating a rapid and permanent\ngrowth of the city. The irhproved con\nditions in the copper industry, includ\ning the expansion tit the local smelters\nand the construction of a new lead\nsmelter here, tile revival of mining\ngenerally, the prosperous condition of\nfarming in the Sulphur Springs valley\nand other sections, and tlie excellent\ncondition of business in general at the\nclose of 1926, all give us plenty of\nreason for optimism concerning 1 927.\n\"The city of Douglas as a whole Is\nIn excellent condition, with compara\ntively little indebtedness, and cash in\nthe banks with which to meet any sud\nden emergency that might befall us.\nThere is no reason why we should not\nmake rapid advancement during the\nnew year.\"\n(Continued on Page Twelve)\nNo. 161","height":"24789","width":"19422"}}
